  "text": "## SharedInformer Factory Architecture in client-go v0.32.0\n\nThe SharedInformer factory is the core mechanism in Kubernetes client-go for maintaining an eventually-consistent local cache of API server resources. The implementation spans multiple key components:\n\n### Factory Registration (informers/factory.go)\nThe `SharedInformerFactory` interface and `sharedInformerFactory` implementation in `informers/factory.go` provides the main entry point. Functions like `NewSharedInformerFactory()` and `NewSharedInformerFactoryWithOptions()` create factory instances. The factory manages:\n- A map of informers indexed by object type\n- Tracking of started vs unstarted informers\n- Resync period configuration (global and per-type)\n- Namespace filtering and list option tweaking\n- Shutdown coordination via WaitGroup\n\nKey methods:\n- `Start()` initializes all registered informers in separate goroutines\n- `Shutdown()` stops all informers and waits for cleanup\n- `WaitForCacheSync()` waits for cache synchronization to complete\n- `InformerFor()` gets or creates a SharedIndexInformer for a given object\n\n### Informer Registration (informers/internalinterfaces/factory_interfaces.go)\nThe internal `SharedInformerFactory` interface defines the minimal contract needed to avoid import cycles. The `NewInformerFunc` type is a function pointer that creates SharedIndexInformers, allowing the factory to instantiate informers for different resource types.\n\n### List-Watch Mechanism (tools/cache/listwatch.go)\nThe `ListerWatcher` interface combines:\n- `List()` method to fetch all objects matching criteria\n- `Watch()` method to receive incremental updates\n\nThe `ListWatch` implementation provides a concrete instance that wraps REST client calls. `NewListWatchFromClient()` creates ListWatch instances for specific resources, handling field selector configuration and options modification.\n\n### Reflector Pattern (tools/cache/reflector.go)\nThe `Reflector` watches a resource via ListerWatcher and syncs all changes to a Store. Key features:\n- Handles List/Watch semantics with exponential backoff for failures\n- Manages resource version tracking for resumable watches\n- Supports pagination with `WatchListPageSize` for large datasets\n- Implements optional watchlist streaming mode (UseWatchList)\n- Customizable error handling via WatchErrorHandler\n- Resync period support for reconciliation\n\nThe Reflector is created by the Controller and drives continuous synchronization with the API server.\n\n### Cache Store Implementations (tools/cache/store.go, tools/cache/index.go)\nThe `Store` interface defines basic cache operations (Add, Update, Delete, Get, List, Replace). The `Indexer` extends Store with indexing capabilities for efficient lookups by field values.\n\n`NewStore()` creates a basic unindexed store using `ThreadSafeStore` as the backend.\n`NewIndexer()` creates an indexed store with configurable index functions.\n\n### Thread-Safe Storage (tools/cache/thread_safe_store.go)\nThe `ThreadSafeStore` interface provides concurrent-safe access to cached objects. Implementation uses:\n- Mutex-protected access to object maps\n- Index structures for efficient field-based queries (NamespaceIndex, etc.)\n- Support for adding indexers dynamically\n\n### DeltaFIFO Queue (tools/cache/delta_fifo.go)\nThe `DeltaFIFO` is a producer-consumer queue that:\n- Stores objects as Deltas (sequence of operations: Added, Updated, Deleted, Replaced, Sync)\n- Acts as the intermediary between Reflector (producer) and event handlers (consumers)\n- Tracks known objects to detect state changes\n- Supports deduplication and ordering guarantees\n\n`NewDeltaFIFOWithOptions()` creates instances with configurable key function and known object tracking.\n\n### Controller Orchestration (tools/cache/controller.go)\nThe `Controller` interface orchestrates the Reflector and DeltaFIFO queue:\n- Created via `New()` with a Config specifying the queue, ListerWatcher, and ProcessFunc\n- `Run()` method starts the Reflector in a goroutine and processes queue items\n- Handles both initial sync and incremental updates\n\n### SharedInformer Event Distribution (tools/cache/shared_informer.go)\nThe `SharedIndexInformer` implementation:\n- Wraps a Controller and Indexer (the cache)\n- Uses `sharedProcessor` to distribute cache events to multiple listeners\n- Each listener is wrapped in a `processorListener` with its own event channel\n- Supports AddEventHandler() to register ResourceEventHandlers\n- Provides HasSynced() to check if initial sync is complete\n- Uses synctrack.Lazy for lazy evaluation of sync state\n\n`NewSharedIndexInformer()` creates instances with optional indexers for performance.\n\n### Synchronization Tracking (tools/cache/synctrack/)\nThe synctrack package provides utilities for tracking sync state across multiple goroutines:\n- `AsyncTracker` helps propagate HasSynced in multi-threaded scenarios\n- `Lazy` provides lazy evaluation with single computation\n- `SingleFileTracker` tracks sync state for individual listeners\n\n### Complete Flow\n1. User calls `NewSharedInformerFactory()` to create a factory\n2. User calls `factory.Start(stopChan)` to initialize all registered informers\n3. Factory creates informers via `InformerFor()` using NewInformerFuncs\n4. Each informer creates a SharedIndexInformer with cache (Indexer) and controller\n5. Controller creates a Reflector with ListerWatcher and DeltaFIFO queue\n6. Reflector starts `ListAndWatch()` which:\n   - Calls ListerWatcher.List() to fetch initial objects\n   - Stores all objects in the DeltaFIFO with Replaced deltas\n   - Calls ListerWatcher.Watch() to receive incremental updates\n   - Adds updates to DeltaFIFO as Added/Updated/Deleted deltas\n7. Controller.Run() processes items from DeltaFIFO:\n   - Pops Deltas and applies them to the Indexer (cache)\n   - Invokes registered event handlers\n8. SharedProcessor distributes events to multiple listeners\n9. Clients query cache via Indexer.Get() or Lister interfaces\n10. User calls `factory.Shutdown()` to cleanly stop all informers\n\nThis architecture provides an eventually-consistent, efficient, and scalable mechanism for keeping local caches in sync with Kubernetes API server state."
